How Travel Prices Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially to the socialist bloc countries, because the western trips were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in Eastern Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was authorized to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination to the west and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (even for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even as part of the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he required an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to do the tail all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition to travel to the west was denied "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovakian currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were many country houses and cottages that the Czechs purchased and this habit lasts until now.
The Czech travel has been a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at the maximum, Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The removal of visas in the 90s of the last century in neighbouring Western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel long by plane west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to carry with it its own conserved food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown that allowed our tourists finally after decades of able to freely buy Western currency.
Our living level as well as average wage increased, which caused another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to an increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have started preparing tours with air charter routes since 1997, which thanks to contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to previously.
In the late 90s of the last century, Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world besides the EU that later facilitated our trips.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct airline charters take Czech tourists to far hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to hold fully in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50,3%) for the first time in history, and spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad, including annexed charges.
