The Court valid "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analog signals with digitals is one of the biggest changes the world has suffered in the last few years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has dismissed the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the House of Deputies formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to invalid it were not gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón has not exceeded his duties when issued the decree detailing the actions to be followed to concretize the transition to digital Earth TV.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as a non-constitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is a law-reserved attribution to the Federal Commission of Telecommunications (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and law reserve.
In favour of the project only voted Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the House of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversys to dispute the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions it provided for for the digital transition.
The plenary meeting of the ministers also decided to dismiss the complaint made by the House of Deputies, without discussing the draft that Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible for.
In his intervention, the President said he was not in agreement with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structur the measures to prepare for the public administration to do so through general standards.
"I also consider that if it was done, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, who has the constitutional mandate of the governance of the State.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this results in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality, and more chains.
It would be to delay the benefits of digitalization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues.
These issues, he emphasized, "requires the operation of an entire system establishing, in accordance with the principle of economic management of the State, a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already finished the digital transition and they have done it through the Executive, despite the fact that they had the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issue of the disputed decree, has invaded in a form the sphere of competences of the Congress, because in the administrative sphere it ensures that the laws issued by the legislative, he assured.
The possibility of counting "voting by vote" in Michoacán is analyzed
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6,000 74 total records.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality regarding the electoral trial this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the Governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 8 thousand to 74b proce.
In this sense, Chair of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards to the federal electoral reform.
It will be remembered that Michoacán has not approved its Political Constitution or its Electoral Code of State or its Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the State Congress has approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline had ended for that electoral trial to be entered into force, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel has omitted the publication of the State.
On the same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) solved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local legislative power and described the vote of the State's official for constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" because it does not have the right to "sanction or dispute them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that through the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to achieve the partial and total vote counts by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more packages, may be that: the results of the proceedings do not coincide; there is no vote record and counting in the case of the urn is not in the president of the urn; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the proceedings.
Furthermore, the total counting of the votes received in all the election urns may be achieved when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate winner of the respective election and the candidate who received the second place in the election is equal or below a percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition of the candidate/represe.
The total count of the vote may also be achieved if at the end of the common count it results that the difference between the alleged winner and that of the second place is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party whose second candidate was released, in which the electoral packages were excluded.
It should be noted that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total proceedings.
