The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government to face a crisis that put the country on the edge of the economic disaster.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government facing a crisis that put Italy on the edge of the economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, named Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed of technocrats in its majority, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the result of his conversations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner for Journalists said.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
“The framework is now well traced,” he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy fights a political and financial crisis that increased its debt costs to levels impossible to support.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a hard package of austerity required by European leaders to recover the trust in Italy that had been affected.
By emphasizing the pressure on Monti to speed, the instability of markets placed the return of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: “We said we would support this government a lot.”
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s opportunities for success were significantly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, to which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts will have a good result,” Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new devastating financial market attack.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employer groups and youth and women organizations on Monday.
He will end his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of €1.9 billion, would be too much for the current financial defenses of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should continue until the future elections, planned for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections advanced.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist on the fact that it should only be formed by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources reported that reciprocal mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
