Quinteto included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
“Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become reality.”
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament from Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday on Stade National.
They have waited for more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream becoming reality to happen in this country.
It is that the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva from Brazil, last week.
The group is located in the South American wing of its two-decade work tour and Sunday 20 will make its unique stopover in Central America.
On that day they will appear at the Stade National, starting at 19:30 a.m., next to the Los Angeles band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an extract from the conversation, whose complete transcription is found in La Nación sur Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream becoming reality. Are you aware of what your fans live?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I only spent the vacation in Costa Rica once; it’s such a beautiful country and I think we’ll be able to spend a few days there.
So it feels like we carry our music there.
I ask you, because there is some sort of devotion to the group, fans live intensely in the past days.
What is your message for your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying next to us all these years.
It took 21 years to reach Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so much and we're sorry that so much time had to spend until this concert.
Some people already say his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add some pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we have offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We offered a two gigantic shows to Sao Paolo and we hope it has shaped us for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to make surfing?
We have a lot of surfers friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; this is how we learned, through the gents who love surfing.
By watching the tour, you birds offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never produced ourselves there, we have no restrictions regarding what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse directory.
You never repeat the directory.
What is it due to?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can interpret more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, that’s why it’s very difficult to choose which songs to interpret every evening.
When we have two or three songs in the directory that we have no longer interpreted for a long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises because it reminds us the reasons why we loved these songs and we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it becomes more interesting to people as well.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you have succeeded?
Yeah, absolutely.
First of all, I think none of us had imagined we would go to form a big rock band, and the fact that we have done it for more than 20 years makes it seem a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the ability to continue to make music together, we feel a lot of emotions.
We love and love creating music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world we always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of large groups.
We are very friends with people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group comes from a city, but it’s much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we are lucky to be still friends with all of them and it is an honour for us to be part of this Seattle sound that emerged.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stays united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
First, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and second, we are all concerned about others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give freedom to everyone to experiment.
We trust each other with everyone’s music and that couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don’t spend too much time on tour because it’s easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we don't forget that people are here for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect music and what has brought it, without taking into account the fact that we're famous and a rock star, which really doesn't interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote good songs and at the beginning it was great.
We were a group for almost three years and we didn’t publish a record before Andy’s death (Andrew Woods).
There was a lot of frustrations for the fact that she lasted so little and most important is the fact that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who began in the band with us and when I listen to a song or see a photo I think about the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh of working, it was always a lot of fun.
He was a surprising human being and we miss it.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and for that you chose her for the opening?
Yes, production has sent us videos with different proposals and that was the group we loved most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and that must be very distracting.
Why do you always change Yello Ledbetter's words live for?
This is a question for Eddie Vedder, so I don’t know.
It is he who sings it and I think he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam succeed in keeping the grunge relevant despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little offline from the word grunge.
When I think of it, it reminds me of the groups I just mentioned, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that have emerged at the same time, and if it’s relevant now, I think that it’s wonderful, because it’s a music worth listening and groups like Mudhoney now make the best music than ever.
At the beginning, her music had darker content and now it became more positive.
What is this change due to?
It’s interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe qualified as very dark songs, even though they can sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cryed when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there is a trauma in your life and you lose a parent or friend, these things begin to influence your art and music and these songs, probably, represent this for me.
