The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetic Obesity of Children and Teenagers' protocol to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Chief of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialties at the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the people who have the right or not are invited to participate in the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence for minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After achieving the objective of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (South of District Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (North of District Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and the objective of knowing the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 years, with their parents' consent and under the supervision, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family heritage of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, size circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol, and insulin and genetics (sought to identify people associated with infant obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of healthcare professionals for alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
“The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years, in the case of boys, there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, there was also a dramatic increase,” IMSS said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
He added that on average, Mexicans have 65% of Indo-American heritage, 30% of European and 5% of African heritage, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, obesity genetics result in the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
It even says that the presence of dark color folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of suffering from metabolic and even prediabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, physicians give it in writing to parents, to whom each is explained the measures and changes in the lifestyle they need to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the highest calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet beverages, carbon hydrates (tamals - corn meat pasted wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high content of fat and protein and genetics analyzed in this protocol.
