This was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A Cali dactyloscopist went into history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4th, a Cali CTI dactyloscopist passed into history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme chief of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven dactyloscopists working in the local offices of the ICT, this week was the tour of “availability” of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to reach the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000, he moved to the capital of Valle and after having had adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he went to Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew he had to identify two corpses and one of them was suspected to be the one of the man who was leading the oldest guerilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his true name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the corpse, he did not recognize it for his physical aspect, because it was very different from that he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But the footprints do not lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian wolf, ink, a breeder and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body with the map.
His eye didn’t mislead him: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the responsible who confirmed to the Minister of Defense Juan Carlos Pinzón that he was the supreme chief of the FARC.
Looking for the footprint
For a Sijín de Cali dactyloscopist the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González at a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without a margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, dactyloscopics support investigations for crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of people captured.
When captured, many offenders have false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search for them in the database.
The researcher told him that in a case of theft he had to remove part of the wall from a house, because in this place the thief had pushed his hand to bring out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint with all our hands and identify the criminal who had participated in different flights," he said.
The footprints may also remove or confirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently we found a dead man with bottles of drink around him.
By intermediate investigation it was determined that a parent may be suspicious of crime and in fact a footprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn’t guarantee that he is the assassin, it places him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents are extracted."
When they appear, a breeder or a strip is used to take them up.
Subsequently, the footprints are sent to Asif, the decline database, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers," the ICT expert said.
He explained that everything is not as shown in the CSI TV program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything that you touch does not strongly become a footprint.
It can, however, be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
