More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated last Tuesday on the edges of the Baltic, between orchestra and end buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte turned together the wheel of the valve commander of Russian gas entry into the western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region with the country of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge building has victory airs.
The project had been heavily disputed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will in fact enable the delivery of gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Therefore, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes harder for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
In the strongest of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means whether the subject is politically sensitive.
West Europe, by giving its support to this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the price of a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a break between Eastern and West Europeans.
Russia knew, in just five years, to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, heavily gas consumers, and whose settlements are declining.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically,” François Fillon confirmed by inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how great gas contracts are as political as well as economic.
All this explains the broad smile posted by Gazprom leaders, present in number at Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical exploitation.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-shaved steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It is located on the bottom of the sea, on average 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mine fields dating back to World War II.
“A hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed by precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It also needed to multiply measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing stops over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but project managers resigned there while the Swedish were unwilling to see a Russian state society permanently established outside their coastlines.
"In the event of awareness, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline is thus escaped into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who planned the welds to experience a leakage every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the gas pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, width of a meter of diameter, and is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters, he delivered accurate information about the possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at departure, and 100 bars at arrival.
Five companies have united their strengths to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture named Nord Stream, charged with the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
She has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where the taxation is particularly favorable.
Gazprom then rented the company, for twenty renewable years, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of actually transported gas,” said Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided at 30% by shareholders and at 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to enter their fees, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, high 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificity of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour spending.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million an hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to give back the taste of writing.
He has a perfume of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine book is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white colour, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine book as we know it today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decides at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is charged with the launch of the new product.
The book is inspired by an old production technique, the soft skin (skin of butterflies) which refers to a cotton lacquer used to cover banks, for example.
This type of book was very favoured by writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has tasted an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine exceeds the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robot portrait of the buyer, as the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open in mind and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its debut, counts nearly 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her bookbooks in bookshops, from the Fnac to small town shops and has been able to impose her identity.
“We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own book.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, schedule, pens, computer covers... The brand declines on a whole range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was purchased by the SG Capital Europe Investment Fund, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of workers with disabilities so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of persons with disabilities is opened today.
Despite voluntary public policy established in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice higher than the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
“No,” says Eric Blanchet, Director-General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress made for fifteen years has been considerable."
“The unemployment rate at the time was not two but three times higher.”
"There is still a lot to be done."
It should be said that for unemployed people, many obstacles remain before access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the box and of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that particularly complicate the return to employment, and that " constitute the node of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for the objective brakes.
It remains not said, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchair, psychological or intellectual deficiencies".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment goal of 6% of disabled workers, as set out in a... 1987 law.
The latest known figures, dating from 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of " taxed " institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, ranging from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates to real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of 100 to 199 employees.
